<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFA9AB09FF2D8D20FEBBFAAB" pageId="11" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFA9AB09FF2D8D20FEBBFAAB" blockId="11.[173,660,1203,1729]" pageId="11">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FF2D8D20FEDCFAFE" bold="true" box="[197,301,1283,1304]" pageId="11">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The oval configuration of the hind body will distinguish the members of this species from congeners.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFA9AB09FF2D8D70FC20FEA7" pageId="11" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFA9AB09FF2D8D70FCBCFEEA" blockId="11.[173,660,1203,1729]" lastBlockId="11.[707,1193,194,454]" pageId="11">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FF2D8D70FE8DFA8E" bold="true" box="[197,380,1363,1384]" pageId="11">Description. Size</emphasis>
: Length 
<quantity id="4C894A9AFFA9AB09FE038D70FDB5FA8E" box="[491,580,1363,1384]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" pageId="11" unit="mm" value="3.5">3.5 mm</quantity>
; width 
<quantity id="4C894A9AFFA9AB09FF458D4DFF0BFA65" box="[173,250,1390,1411]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="11" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FEED8D4DFECCFA65" bold="true" box="[261,317,1390,1411]" pageId="11">Form</emphasis>
: As in 
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFA9AB09FE618D4DFE23FA65" box="[393,466,1390,1411]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="22.[175,215,1444,1463]" captionTargetBox="[167,1157,203,1421]" captionTargetId="figure-120@22.[167,1157,192,1421]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="Figs. 98–103. Pujoliclerus species, habitus. 98) P. ovatus; 99) P. wappesi; 100) P. amplus; 101) P. flavoapicalus;" pageId="11">Fig. 98</figureCitation>
. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FE348D4DFDA8FA65" bold="true" box="[476,601,1390,1411]" pageId="11">Integument:</emphasis>
Head mostly yellow, with dark streak; antenna mostly brown, apex yellow; lateral pronotal sides yellow, brown at middle; fore legs mostly brown, base of profemur yellow, remainder of legs yellow and brown, pterothorax and abdomen brown. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FF458E2EFF12F9C4" bold="true" box="[173,227,1549,1570]" pageId="11">Head</emphasis>
: Eyes as wide as frons (10:10); funicular antennomeres slightly expanded, 6 
<superScript id="7C044A37FFA9AB09FDE98E01FDFEF9D6" attach="left" box="[513,527,1570,1584]" fontSize="6" pageId="11">th</superScript>
antennomere acuminate (
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFA9AB09FEC98E61FE9FF9B1" box="[289,366,1602,1623]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="8.[175,216,1487,1506]" captionTargetBox="[167,1170,207,1464]" captionTargetId="figure-1@8.[151,1172,183,1487]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figs. 21–38. Pujoliclerus species, antennae. 21) P. helvinus; 22) P. maracayensis; 23) P. bilineatus; 24) P. calceatus; 25) P. corumba; 26) P. ovatus; 27) P. wappesi; 28) P. amplus; 29) P. flavoapicalus; 30) P. gilvus; 31) P. hermani; 32) P. alajuela; 33) P. orellana; 34) P. megacavus; 35) P. oxinus; 36) P. alboordinus; 37) P. apolegmus; 38) P. catarina." pageId="11">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FE6C8E61FE21F9B1" bold="true" box="[388,464,1602,1623]" pageId="11">Thorax</emphasis>
: Pronotum slightly transverse (30:27), lateral tubercle prominent (
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFA9AB09FF5C8E54FEF7F96A" box="[180,262,1655,1676]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="18.[175,215,1395,1414]" captionTargetBox="[151,1155,183,1382]" captionTargetId="figure-114@18.[151,1172,183,1383]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs. 48–61. Pujoliclerus species, pronota. 48) P. helvinus; 49) P. maracayensis; 50) P. modestus; 51) P. bilineatus; 52) P. calceatus; 53) P. corumba; 54) P. flavolimbatus; 55) P. ovatus; 56) P. wappesi; 57) P. amplus; 58) P. flavoapicalus; 59) P. gilvus; 60) P. hermani; 61) P. orellana." pageId="11">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
); asetiferous punctures end at about elytral half, epipleural fold wide, gradually diminishing to elytral apex; asetiferous punctures prominent in anterior elytral half. 
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FBD188E1FB53FF31" bold="true" box="[1081,1186,194,215]" pageId="11">Abdomen</emphasis>
: Male pygidium incised distally; tegminal lobes as in 
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFA9AB09FD1688D4FCB8FEEA" box="[766,841,247,268]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="20.[175,215,1170,1189]" captionTargetBox="[164,629,189,1147]" captionTargetId="figure-461@20.[151,638,183,1159]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="Figs. 76–91. Pujoliclerus species, aedeagi. 76) P. helvinus; 77) P. bilineatus; 78) P. calceatus; 79) P. corumba; 80) P. flavolimbatus; 81) P. ovatus (tegmen only); 82) P. wappesi; 83) P. gilvus; 84) P. hermani; 85) P. casselorum; 86) P. catarina (phallus only); 87) P. argus; 88) P. aspigalbus; 89) P. flora; 90) P. posticalis; 91) P. pallidus." pageId="11">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFA9AB09FD338931FC20FEA7" blockId="11.[707,1193,194,454]" pageId="11">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FD338931FC72FEC1" bold="true" box="[731,899,274,295]" pageId="11">Natural History.</emphasis>
The 
<typeStatus id="54CA59DDFFA9AB09FC538931FC12FEC1" box="[955,995,274,295]" pageId="11">type</typeStatus>
was collected during October in a blacklight trap.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFA9AB09FD338964FCBAFE91" pageId="11" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFA9AB09FD338964FCBAFE91" blockId="11.[707,1193,194,454]" pageId="11">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FD338964FCACFEBA" bold="true" box="[731,861,327,348]" pageId="11">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54CA59DDFFA9AB09FBAB8964FB9DFEBA" box="[1091,1132,327,348]" pageId="11">type</typeStatus>
locality (
<figureCitation id="134AFBFAFFA9AB09FD038941FCB1FE91" box="[747,832,354,375]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="26.[709,741,859,878]" captionTargetBox="[206,1171,184,835]" captionTargetId="figure-18@26.[685,1172,183,836]" captionTargetPageId="26" captionText="Fig. 123. Geographic distribution of six Pujoliclerus species." pageId="11">Fig. 123</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36BB4F4FFA9AB09FD33895FFB8BFE20" pageId="11" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BCEE77FFFA9AB09FD33895FFB8BFE20" blockId="11.[707,1193,194,454]" pageId="11">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FD33895FFCBCFE77" bold="true" box="[731,845,380,401]" pageId="11">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet 
<taxonomicName id="4C719CFCFFA9AB09FBF68958FBADFE76" authorityName="Opitz" authorityYear="2014" box="[1054,1116,379,400]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Pujoliclerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ovatus">
<emphasis id="B9053B6DFFA9AB09FBF68958FBADFE76" box="[1054,1116,379,400]" italics="true" pageId="11">ovatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(= eggshaped) is a Latin adjective that refers to the oval configuration of the hind body of this beetle.
</paragraph>
